          "title": "Task A",
          "content": "Computer networks are systems that allow multiple computing devices to communicate and share resources. These networks can range from small local area networks (LANs) in homes and offices to vast wide area networks (WANs) connecting cities and countries. The primary purpose of networking is to enable devices to exchange data efficiently, improving collaboration, data access, and resource sharing.\n\nThe two most common types of networks are LANs and WANs. LANs typically cover a small geographical area, such as an office building or school, while WANs span large distances, often using leased telecommunication lines. Other variations include metropolitan area networks (MANs) and personal area networks (PANs), each serving specific needs.\n\nNetwork devices are critical in managing data flow. Key devices include routers, which direct data between networks; switches, which manage data traffic within a LAN; hubs, which are basic data distribution devices; and access points, which enable wireless connectivity. Understanding these devices and their roles lays the foundation for more advanced networking studies.",
