          "content": "Network communication relies on standard protocols to ensure devices interpret data correctly. Two fundamental models describe this communication process: the OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model and the TCP/IP model.\n\nThe OSI model is a conceptual framework divided into seven layers: Physical, Data Link, Network, Transport, Session, Presentation, and Application. Each layer performs specific functions, such as addressing (Network layer), error correction (Data Link layer), or data encryption (Presentation layer). Understanding these layers helps network professionals isolate issues and design robust networks.\n\nIn contrast, the TCP/IP model, which is the foundation of the internet, has four layers: Network Interface, Internet, Transport, and Application. Though simpler, it maps closely to OSI functions. Key protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) handle addressing and routing, while TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) ensures reliable data delivery.\n\nGrasping these models allows you to understand how emails, web pages, and video calls are transmitted across the globe.",
