          "content": "IP addressing and subnetting are crucial concepts in managing network traffic efficiently. An IP address uniquely identifies a device on a network. IPv4, the most commonly used version, uses a 32-bit address format, typically expressed in dotted-decimal notation (e.g., 192.168.1.1). IPv6, the newer version, utilizes 128-bit addresses to accommodate the growing number of internet-connected devices.\n\nSubnetting divides a large network into smaller, manageable segments (subnets), improving performance and security. Subnet masks determine which portion of an IP address represents the network and which part denotes the host. For example, a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0 indicates that the first three octets are the network identifier.\n\nCIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) notation, such as /24, simplifies subnetting representation. Mastery of IP addressing and subnetting is essential for network administrators to design scalable and efficient networks.",
