          "title": "Task A",
          "content": "Classical mechanics extends into more complex systems involving rotational dynamics and fluid mechanics. Rotational motion involves angular displacement, velocity, and acceleration, governed by torque (τ = r × F) and moment of inertia, which reflects an object's resistance to rotational acceleration. For example, a figure skater pulling in their arms to spin faster illustrates the conservation of angular momentum. Additionally, fluid dynamics, encompassing the study of liquids and gases in motion, introduces Bernoulli's Principle, which relates pressure, velocity, and height in a flowing fluid. This principle explains how airplanes generate lift and how carburetors regulate fuel flow. Mastery of these topics requires integrating force analysis with rotational kinematics and understanding real-world applications like turbines, propellers, and hydraulic systems.",
