          "content": "Modern physics emerged to address limitations of classical theories in explaining phenomena at atomic and cosmological scales. Albert Einstein's Theory of Relativity, comprising Special and General Relativity, revolutionized our understanding of space, time, and gravity. Special Relativity introduced the concept that the laws of physics are the same in all inertial frames, and that the speed of light is a constant. This led to profound implications such as time dilation and mass-energy equivalence (E = mc²), which have practical applications in GPS technology and nuclear energy. General Relativity, extending this framework to accelerated frames and gravitational fields, describes gravity not as a force but as a curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy. This theory predicts phenomena like gravitational lensing and black holes, which are now observed with modern telescopes.",
