        {
          "title": "Task B",
          "content": "Mathematical modeling involves creating abstract representations of real-world systems to analyze and predict behavior. Models can be deterministic, providing exact outcomes based on inputs, or probabilistic, incorporating elements of randomness. Examples of mathematical modeling include predicting population growth, modeling the spread of diseases, optimizing supply chains, and simulating financial markets. Building effective models requires a combination of mathematical knowledge, critical thinking, and computational skills. It also involves validating models against empirical data and refining them to improve accuracy. As the world becomes increasingly data-driven, mathematical modeling stands at the forefront of decision-making processes in science, business, and public policy.",
          "questions": [
            {
              "question": "What is the primary purpose of mathematical modeling?",
              "options": [
                "To perform simple arithmetic",
                "To create visual art using geometry",
                "To represent and analyze real-world systems",
                "To memorize mathematical formulas"
              ],
              "answer": "To represent and analyze real-world systems"
            }
          ],
          "recommendedTopics": [
            "Introduction to Mathematical Modeling",
            "Deterministic vs Probabilistic Models",
            "Model Validation Techniques"
          ]
        }
